Food safety should be a top priority for any establishment, especially one that prides itself on quality. The lack of concern from the management was unacceptable. This kind of negligence could lead to severe health consequences, especially for children.
Whole Foods, I urge you to take this issue seriously. Proper food preparation and customer safety should never be overlooked. I hope to see accountability and improvement so that no other family has to experience this.

There weren't any napkins, so I eventually wiped my hands on the counter just to get the grease off them. After being loyal WFM customers since 2009, we've decided we will no longer give our business to Whole Foods.
- produce quality is just awful. Every single time we go shopping, we find produce just rotting on the shelves. And the pattern continues, with half of the purchase rotting in the fridge within a day or two. And no, it's not because it's organic, we buy a mix of conventional and organic.
- the hot bar - the sizzler has a better selection and quality. Selection is abysmal and on multiple occasions I've gotten food that is undercooked or spoiled (tasted and smelled sour). I'm not even mentioning the food that is dry and crusty bc it's been sitting out for hours.
- bakery items are subpar at best. Pastries are almost always undercooked, and why don't they slice bread for customers anymore?
- grocery shelves are half empty and items are out of stock for weeks.
- lastly, I'd like to comment on the poor workers, who are lifeless, clearly overwhelmed and overworked and sometimes rude and frustrated. Why does it take 20 minutes to get some cheese sliced at the deli? I don't blame them, I blame the management, because it is so evident that the managers are apathetic to workers needs.
Farewell WFM and congratulations to Amazon for ruining a good thing.
